Social Interactions at a Public High School

Lauren Treiman

8/3/2018

This analysis was used to help an epidimeoly research project at the University of Utah investigate how interactions spread viruses such as the flu. This file contains the social network analysis for one high school in Salt Lake City. To obtain the data, students wore sensors that recorded how long and who a student interacted with. Students wore these sensors for two whole school days.

For this project, I used R-markdown to create the html document and used packages such as igraph, dplyr, chron, and lubridate.

Summary of Network

There are two networks for each day of the experiment. There are 4 90 minute periods, 3 6 minute hallway passings, and 2 30 minute lunches.

Day 1

## IGRAPH 7e9b037 UN-- 1425 153999 --

For day 1, there were 1425 students who participated and 153999 interactions. Day 2

## IGRAPH a6224fa UN-- 1220 556935 -- 
## + attr: name (v/c), GradeCat (v/n), GenderCat (v/n), Lunch (v/n),

## | Duration (e/n), period (e/c)

For day 2, there were 1220 students who participated and 556935 interavtions.

Distribution

I graphed the distribution of the number of interactions for each hallway, period and lunches, and after school. Both lunches are grouped together. Also, it is important to note that sensors were handed out to students in period 1, so there is an overestimate of total interactions for period 1.

Interactions Throughout the Day

Assortativity

I looked at 4 different reasons why a student would be more likely to interact with another student: if they were the same gender, in the same grade, had the same lunch, or interacted with the same number of students.
